article.description: Rebekkah Brunson scored 16 points and the visiting Sacramento Monarchs beat Charlotte 76-58 on Thursday night, spoiling the debut of Sting coach Muggsy Bogues.

related.description:
Muggsy Bogues was hired Wednesday as coach of the struggling Charlotte Sting, replacing Trudi Lacey, who
will remain as the team's general manager.
related.title: Bogues new coach; Lacey to remain Sting GM
related.headline: Bogues new coach; Lacey to remain Sting GM

article.headline: Brunson, Griffith lead Sacramento to sixth straight win
article.linkText: Visiting Monarchs spoil Bogues' debut in Charlotte
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Muggsy Bogues started his first postgame
news conference as a coach by calling his players "guys." He
quickly stopped, started the sentence over, and called them
"girls."

Bogues has to get comfortable with his new position.

Rebekkah Brunson scored a career-high 16 points and the
Sacramento Monarchs beat Charlotte 76-58 on Thursday night,
spoiling Bogues' debut as Sting coach.

Yolanda Griffith added 14 points and eight rebounds for the
Monarchs (19-7), who matched a franchise record with their sixth
straight win.

Tammy Sutton-Brown scored 13 points for the Sting (3-22), who
committed 24 turnovers in their club-record 10th straight loss.

The 5-foot-3 Bogues, who spent a decade as the point guard for
the Charlotte Hornets, replaced Trudi Lacey as coach Wednesday.

Walking onto the floor five minutes before tipoff, the small
crowd greeted Bogues with a loud ovation. Dressed in a black suit
with a pink shirt and tie, the former Charlotte crowd favorite
waved to the fans.

"That felt good, it was a warm welcome," Bogues said. "It's
always fun to come back in this arena. I have some fond memories.
It's good to be back home."

Bogues, known for his fast-paced style as a player, had said he
wanted the Sting to take the same approach. It worked early, as
Charlotte scored twice on the fast break and took an 8-2 lead. But
the uptempo style also led to mistakes. Charlotte hit six of its
first 11 shots, but trailed 17-12 because of eight turnovers.

The turnover total reached 14 at halftime as Sacramento led
37-29.

"Muggsy wants to pick up the tempo and I told him tonight I
think he'll get it done," Monarchs coach John Whisenant said. "We
lead the league in turnovers created. That's why we are where we
are. We're not that much different from a lot of teams on the
offensive end."

Former Sting first-round draft pick Nicole Powell, who was
traded by Lacey to Sacramento in the offseason, hit a 3-pointer to
make it 52-38 with 14:46 left. The Monarchs, who moved within a
half-game of league-leading Connecticut, went on to lead by as many
as 19 points.

"We're on a mission to win the West and get homecourt advantage
and every four-minute stretch is important to us," Whisenant said.
"We stayed focused tonight."

Bogues, coaching his first game at any level, was calm most of
the first half, leaving his seat mostly to cheer made baskets. He
had only a couple of brief exchanges with the referees, while he
had lengthy discussions with assistant coaches Cheryl Reeve and
Fred Chmiel before addressing the team during timeouts.

He seemed to become more comfortable and more animated in the
second half, pacing the sideline and arguing calls more vehemently.

"I wasn't nervous at all," Bogues said. "I was anxious to see
how they were going to perform. It's going to take some time, and
they have to be patient. For the most part they did what I asked,
we just didn't protect the basketball."

Helen Darling, the Sting's starting point guard after Dawn
Staley was traded to Houston on Monday, had 10 assists and nine
turnovers. The Monarchs scored 28 points off Charlotte miscues.

"We put in a number of new plays and we have a number of new
players who don't know the old plays," Sutton-Brown said. "We
have to stay together. He knows the game. He understands the game
of basketball and is using that as his strength right now."
